{"id": "4d57935b5bd743bf99fe959940e0ad7a", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:35:59", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: The proposed research topic represents a significant and innovative advancement in the intersection of AI, human-computer interaction, and machine translation post-editing. By shifting from discrete command-based interactions to a continuous, intent-driven model grounded in spatiotemporal gesture analysis, the direction addresses a clear gap in current systems: the inefficiency of sequential delete-then-insert workflows. The integration of multimodal signals—digital ink, gaze, context—and the development of a contextual \"repair decoder\" trained on professional edit rationales introduce novel technical components with strong practical grounding. The focus on real-time intent anticipation through gesture-as-thought-trace is both original and impactful, particularly for high-pressure, accuracy-critical domains like diplomacy and crisis response. Furthermore, the plan for the InkEdit-MT dataset ensures empirical rigor and generalizability, while the potential for adaptive personalization and accessibility extensions increases its broader scientific and societal value. The topic is technically scoping yet ambitious, aligns with our team’s expertise, and enables concrete prototyping and evaluation pathways. It is therefore both feasible and poised for high impact.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"How can gesture-enhanced handwriting be effectively combined with contextual insertion mechanics to support efficient deletion and modification of machine-translated text?\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[94mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "382c6b0d07cf4458a4e85efab4622e6c", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:36:04", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "The selected research topic focuses on integrating gesture-enhanced handwriting with contextual insertion mechanics to improve the efficiency of editing machine-translated text. Key innovations include treating gestures as \"thought traces\" to anticipate user intent, developing a spatiotemporal fusion model that combines digital ink, gaze, and context, and designing a contextual repair decoder trained on professional editing rationales. The approach aims to replace inefficient delete-then-insert workflows with a seamless, bidirectional editing system. Plans include creating the InkEdit-MT dataset, building a multimodal transformer prototype, conducting pilot studies with translators, and pursuing IRB approval. The topic is feasible, aligns with team expertise, and supports high-impact applications in domains like diplomacy and crisis response. Immediate next steps involve prototyping, grant preparation, and initiating data collection.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[94mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "e61bec2df82f4834afb1706dddee1c78", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:36:41", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The existing research on multimodal post-editing of machine-translated text has made significant strides by incorporating mid-air gestures (Paper 1), pen/touch/speech interfaces (Paper 2), and even LLM-driven gesture generation from speech (Paper 3). However, these approaches remain largely siloed—either focusing on input modalities for editing or on gesture synthesis from linguistic content, but not integrating them into a unified, context-aware interaction framework. My key insight is that the future of efficient post-editing lies not in simply adding more modalities, but in *orchestrating* them intelligently through contextual understanding. Specifically, gesture-enhanced handwriting can be dramatically improved if it is semantically grounded—not just spatially interpreted—by leveraging large language models to predict user intent during correction tasks. Unlike prior work that treats gestures as low-level commands (e.g., “delete this word”), I propose a system where handwritten strokes and hand gestures are jointly interpreted with the surrounding linguistic context to infer high-level editing operations such as \"replace this phrase with a more formal alternative\" or \"restructure this sentence for clarity.\" This shifts the paradigm from direct manipulation to *intent-based editing*, reducing cognitive load and increasing precision. Crucially, this approach integrates the best aspects of Papers 1–3: the physical expressiveness of gestures (Paper 1), the naturalness of pen input (Paper 2), and the semantic power of LLMs in interpreting body-language-like inputs (Paper 3)—but synthesizes them into a novel architecture where handwriting and gestures are not just inputs, but *contextual signals* that an LLM interprets alongside the text being edited. The novelty lies in treating gesture-enhanced handwriting as a form of *multimodal code-switching* between human expression and machine understanding, mediated by an LLM that translates both linguistic and gestural cues into precise, context-sensitive edits.\n\nNew Idea: ```json{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose a novel AI-augmented interface called \\u2018Gesture-Ink Translator\\u2019 (GIT), which fuses real-time gesture-enhanced handwriting with contextual insertion mechanics powered by large language models (LLMs) to enable intelligent, intent-driven post-editing of machine-translated text. In GIT, users write corrections or annotations directly on digital text using a stylus, while concurrent hand gestures (e.g., circling a phrase, swiping over words) provide meta-commands such as deletion, replacement, or rephrasing intent. Instead of treating these inputs as isolated actions, GIT uses a multimodal transformer encoder to jointly embed the spatial-temporal features of handwriting strokes and hand gestures with the semantic context of the source and machine-translated text. An LLM then decodes this fused representation into executable editing operations, predicting not only what action to perform (e.g., delete, insert, reorder) but also *how* to perform it meaningfully—such as suggesting fluent replacements when a user underlines a phrase and makes a 'change' gesture. For instance, a user might circle a poorly translated clause and draw a quick arrow to the margin with a handwritten synonym; GIT interprets this entire multimodal trace as a request to replace the circled text with a contextually appropriate variant generated by the LLM. This reduces the need for precise cursor placement or sequential keystrokes, enabling fluid, continuous editing. The system dynamically adapts its interpretation based on domain (e.g., legal vs. conversational), user history, and translation confidence scores, further personalizing the experience. By unifying gesture, ink, and language understanding within a single predictive framework, GIT moves beyond mechanical editing toward cognitive offloading, allowing translators to focus on high-level meaning rather than low-level manipulation. Potential impact includes reduced post-editing time, lower error rates, and enhanced accessibility for non-keyboard-centric workflows, particularly in mobile or constrained environments.\",\n  \"Title\": \"GIT: Gesture-Ink Translator – Intent-Driven Post-Editing of Machine Translation via Multimodal LLM Fusion\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The implementation will proceed in four phases. Phase 1 involves collecting a multimodal dataset of professional translators performing post-editing tasks using a stylus and hand gestures (tracked via depth camera) on a tablet interface. Participants will edit MT output across diverse domains (technical, literary, conversational), with screen recordings, stroke data, gesture logs, and eye-tracking included. Phase 2 focuses on model development: a multimodal encoder (based on ViT + Transformer) will process ink and gesture sequences, fused with BERT-style embeddings of source and target text. This joint representation will condition a fine-tuned LLM (e.g., Llama-3 or Mistral) to generate editing actions in a structured format (e.g., {'action': 'replace', 'span': [i,j], 'suggestion': '...'}). Phase 3 involves building the interactive prototype using a tablet with hand tracking (e.g., Intel RealSense) and a responsive UI that visualizes predicted edits in real time. Phase 4 is a comparative user study with 20 professional translators, evaluating GIT against baseline conditions (keyboard-only, pen+mouse, and MMPE-like multimodal setup). Metrics include task completion time, edit accuracy, cognitive load (NASA-TLX), and subjective satisfaction. Ideal outcomes include at least a 25% reduction in editing time compared to baselines, high agreement between predicted and intended edits (>80%), and strong qualitative endorsement of the system's intuitiveness and contextual awareness.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 7,\n  \"Novelty\": 10\n}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[91mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "6154044b6fdd4003a2b5ca1cf29200c3", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:37:18", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The original idea of GIT is strong, combining gesture, ink, and LLMs for post-editing machine-translated (MT) text. However, it treats handwriting and gestures as parallel input modalities to be fused with language context—missing a deeper cognitive alignment between how humans *imagine* edits and how they *express* them physically. Inspired by Paper 1’s notion of treating gestures as \"body language\" interpretable via LLMs, and Paper 3’s use of *generative imagination* in translation, I propose shifting from mere multimodal fusion to **intent modeling through embodied cognition**. Rather than just decoding strokes and swipes, the system should simulate the user’s *conceptual intent*—what they imagine the corrected text should convey—by interpreting their physical actions as symbolic expressions of linguistic transformation. This leads to a novel framework where gesture-enhanced handwriting is not just an interface layer but a *cognitive proxy* for semantic re-imagining. Unlike Paper 2, which uses gestures for low-level commands (e.g., delete, select), or GIT, which maps gestures to editing actions, my idea introduces **Imagined Edit Decoding (IED)**: a process where the system infers high-level editorial intentions (e.g., “this sentence sounds unnatural,” “this term needs domain-specific precision”) from the spatial arrangement, pressure dynamics, and gestural flow of handwritten annotations, then leverages an LLM to regenerate fluent, context-aware replacements that match the *intended meaning*, not just the literal input. This approach uniquely integrates *motor intentionality*—the idea that how one writes reflects what one means—with contextual language generation, enabling more intuitive, cognitively efficient editing. It differs fundamentally by treating handwriting not as data entry but as a form of *semantic sketching*, akin to drawing a mental picture of desired output.\n\nNew Idea: ```json{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose \\u2018Imagined Edit Decoding\\u2019 (IED), a cognitive-augmented AI framework that interprets gesture-enhanced handwriting during post-editing of machine-translated text as expressive signals of conceptual intent, rather than literal correction commands. In IED, users annotate MT output using a stylus on a tablet, employing naturalistic behaviors such as underlining with varying pressure, scribbling over mistranslations, drawing arrows to margin notes, or circling phrases with hesitation pauses—all of which are captured as spatio-temporal ink features. Concurrent hand gestures (e.g., pinching to compress meaning, open-palm hovering to indicate uncertainty) are tracked via depth sensors and integrated into a unified behavioral stream. Crucially, IED does not treat these inputs as direct edit instructions; instead, it models them as manifestations of the user's 'edit imagination'—their internal representation of how the text should be transformed. A dual-stream neural architecture first encodes motoric cues (stroke velocity, pen lift frequency, gesture smoothness) into an 'intentionality embedding' using a temporal convolutional network, while a vision transformer processes the spatial layout of ink and gesture. These are fused with source-target context embeddings from a multilingual LLM (e.g., NLLB). The combined representation conditions a generative LLM to predict not only the type of edit (delete, replace, reorder) but also the *semantic direction* of change—such as 'make more formal,' 'simplify syntax,' or 'use technical synonym'—by analyzing patterns in motor behavior correlated with specific editorial goals. For example, aggressive scribbling followed by a downward swipe may signal rejection of tone, prompting the LLM to generate a neutral alternative; light underlining with a marginal doodle of a scale might suggest a need for balance or neutrality. The system learns these mappings through supervised pre-training on a dataset labeled with both explicit edits and inferred intent categories derived from translator interviews and eye-gaze dwell time. During inference, IED offers real-time suggestions that align with the user's imagined improvement, reducing cognitive load by externalizing internal editorial reasoning. This paradigm shifts post-editing from mechanical correction to collaborative ideation, particularly benefiting nuanced domains like legal, literary, or diplomatic translation where meaning subtleties matter. By grounding LLM-driven text generation in embodied human behavior, IED enables faster, more accurate, and semantically richer interactions compared to command-based interfaces.\",\n  \"Title\": \"Imagined Edit Decoding: Modeling Motor Intentionality in Handwritten Post-Editing of Machine Translation\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The implementation will follow five phases. Phase 1 involves designing a controlled elicitation study with 25 professional translators who perform post-editing tasks across three domains (legal, medical, conversational) using a stylus and mid-air gestures on a tablet equipped with force-sensitive input and Intel RealSense tracking. All sessions are recorded with synchronized logging of stroke data (x,y,t,pressure,tilt), gesture trajectories, eye movements (via Tobii eye-tracker), and audio think-aloud protocols. Annotations are later coded into intent categories (e.g., 'reject tone', 'seek precision') via grounded theory analysis. Phase 2 focuses on dataset construction: we extract over 10,000 annotated edit episodes, each paired with motor features and intent labels, forming the IMAGINE-MT corpus. Phase 3 develops the IED model: a Temporal Intention Encoder (TCN-based) learns motor intentionality patterns, while a ViT-Gestalt module captures spatial semantics of ink-gesture layouts. These are fused with mBERT-encoded text contexts and fed to a fine-tuned Llama-3-8B to generate structured edit intents and candidate revisions. Phase 4 builds a real-time prototype with AR feedback overlays showing predicted intent ('You seem to want a more concise version') and suggested edits. Phase 5 conducts a within-subjects user study comparing IED against GIT and keyboard-only baselines, measuring task efficiency, edit quality (BLEU, TER, expert ratings), perceived cognitive effort (NASA-TLX), and alignment between actual and inferred intent. Ideal outcomes include >75% accuracy in intent classification, 30% faster editing times versus baselines, and significant improvements in translation adequacy and fluency scores.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 7,\n  \"Novelty\": 10\n}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[91mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "d51e5f622f1a43138e1afa567c7bfa7c", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:37:45", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: The existing research on multimodal post-editing of machine-translated text has made significant strides by integrating alternative input modalities—such as hand gestures, pen, touch, and speech—to improve efficiency in editing tasks. However, these approaches often treat modalities in isolation or as parallel alternatives rather than deeply integrated components that can inform and enhance one another. Paper 1 demonstrates the potential of mid-air gestures for fine-grained editing, while Paper 2 highlights the strengths of pen and touch for deletion and reordering, and speech for insertion. Paper 3 introduces a novel concept of treating gestures as a \"language\" interpretable by LLMs, suggesting that gesture semantics can be modeled symbolically and contextually. My key insight is that **gesture-enhanced handwriting**—a combination of dynamic pen strokes with embedded gestural meaning—has not been fully exploited as a semantically rich, context-aware input stream. Moreover, current systems lack intelligent contextual insertion mechanics that anticipate user intent during post-editing, especially when correcting machine-translated text where linguistic context is crucial. By unifying symbolic gesture recognition (inspired by GesTran’s LLM-based translation of gestures) with real-time interpretation of handwritten edits, we can create a system where the *form* of a stroke (e.g., a scratch-out vs. a looped selection) and its *content* (handwritten replacement text) are jointly interpreted within the linguistic context of the surrounding MT output. This enables not just faster editing, but *semantically aware* editing—where the system predicts whether a gesture implies deletion, substitution, or restructuring based on both motion and language. Unlike prior work, this idea fuses low-level gesture physics with high-level language understanding via LLMs, creating a bidirectional interface: handwriting informs gesture, gesture informs language model, and language model anticipates next action. This integration offers a leap beyond modality coexistence toward true multimodal synergy.\n\nNew Idea: ```json\n{\n  \"Idea\": \"This research proposes a novel multimodal interface called 'Gesture-Ink Fusion' (GIF), which integrates gesture-enhanced digital handwriting with contextual language modeling to enable intelligent, efficient post-editing of machine-translated text. The core innovation lies in treating handwritten strokes not merely as text input or isolated gestures, but as dual-channel signals: the spatial-temporal dynamics of the stroke encode gestural intent (e.g., delete, replace, move), while the ink content conveys lexical replacement. A large language model (LLM) is trained to jointly interpret these two streams within the syntactic and semantic context of the surrounding machine-translated sentence. For instance, a fast, jagged cross-out stroke over a mistranslated word triggers a deletion command, and if followed immediately by handwritten text in proximity, the system uses contextual fluency scoring to determine whether this constitutes a direct replacement, paraphrase, or structural revision. Crucially, the LLM dynamically adjusts insertion points and grammatical form based on the detected gesture type and linguistic environment. The system employs a two-stage architecture: first, a transformer-based gesture encoder maps stroke features (velocity, pressure, curvature) into discrete gesture primitives (e.g., 'scratch-delete', 'loop-select', 'drag-reorder'); second, a fine-tuned LLM processes the combined sequence of source text, MT output, gesture tokens, and ink content to generate the most probable corrected output. Real-time feedback is provided through subtle UI cues (e.g., fade-on-delete, predictive text boxes). This approach significantly reduces cognitive load by aligning natural handwriting behaviors with intelligent context-aware corrections, enabling translators to edit fluidly without switching tools or modes. The potential impact spans human-computer interaction, AI-assisted translation, and accessible interfaces for multilingual content creation, particularly benefiting domains requiring rapid, accurate localization such as diplomacy, journalism, and emergency response.\",\n  \"Title\": \"Gesture-Ink Fusion: Context-Aware Handwriting and Gesture Integration for Intelligent Post-Editing of Machine Translation\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The implementation will proceed in four phases. Phase 1 involves collecting a multimodal dataset from professional translators using a Wacom tablet and motion-capture stylus while post-editing diverse MT outputs across languages (e.g., English-French, Chinese-English). Participants will perform standard editing tasks (delete, insert, reorder, replace), with all ink, timing, pressure, and gesture data recorded. Phase 2 focuses on gesture primitive classification: a convolutional-recurrent network will be trained to classify six core gesture types (scratch, circle, swipe, drag, flick, write) from stroke dynamics, achieving >90% accuracy on held-out test data. Phase 3 involves building the unified LLM pipeline: gesture tokens and segmented ink regions will be serialized into a prompt format alongside source and MT text, then fed into a fine-tuned BART or T5 model to predict the final corrected sentence. The model will be optimized using BLEU, TER, and human adequacy ratings. Phase 4 consists of a within-subjects user study comparing GIF against baseline (keyboard/mouse) and pen-only conditions, measuring task completion time, error rate, and subjective workload (NASA-TLX). Ideal outcomes include: (1) 25% faster editing speed with GIF, (2) higher correction accuracy, (3) strong user preference for gesture-ink fusion, and (4) demonstration of LLM's ability to resolve ambiguous edits via context.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 10\n}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[94mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "c8bd57cac30d45b5878a938ee2f1acb7", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:38:35", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: While the original \"Gesture-Ink Fusion\" (GIF) idea presents a compelling integration of handwriting and gesture for post-editing machine-translated text, it primarily focuses on 2D tablet-based gestures and assumes that all meaningful signals originate from inked strokes. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s exploration of mid-air gestures and Papers 2–3’s use of LLMs to interpret non-textual modalities as symbolic languages, I propose a more expansive multimodal framework: one that decouples gestural intent from physical contact, allowing users to switch seamlessly between in-air and on-surface input while maintaining contextual awareness. The key innovation lies in treating *all* user motion—whether hovering above the tablet or writing on it—as part of a continuous intention space. This enables richer, faster editing commands (e.g., deleting a phrase with a swipe in the air, then replacing it with handwritten input) without mode switching. Crucially, instead of classifying gestures into discrete primitives early in the pipeline, my approach uses an LLM to *co-embed* spatiotemporal motion features and linguistic context into a shared latent space, enabling fluid interpretation of ambiguous or hybrid inputs. Unlike prior work, this system does not treat gesture and text as separate channels but fuses them at the semantic level, where the LLM learns to resolve intent through contextual inference—similar to how humans interpret mixed verbal and bodily cues. Furthermore, by incorporating predictive insertion mechanics trained on translation error patterns, the model can anticipate likely corrections based on both gesture dynamics and syntactic anomalies in the MT output. This results in a more natural, cognitively aligned interface that reduces motor load and supports rapid iterative refinement.\n\nNew Idea: ```json{\n  \"Idea\": \"This research introduces 'FluidEdit', a context-aware, multimodal post-editing interface that unifies in-air hand gestures, digital handwriting, and large language model (LLM)-driven contextual reasoning to enable seamless, low-latency correction of machine-translated (MT) text. FluidEdit advances beyond existing gesture-enhanced systems by treating user motion as a continuous spectrum of expressive intent—ranging from hover-based navigation to contact-based writing—rather than segmented input modes. The core contribution is a unified neural architecture that co-processes three streams: (1) fine-grained stylus motion data (including pressure, tilt, velocity, and proximity-to-surface), (2) spatial-temporal hand trajectory from a depth sensor (for mid-air gestures), and (3) the linguistic context of source and MT text. These modalities are jointly embedded into a shared representation space using a cross-modal transformer, where an LLM is trained to decode *intentional semantics* directly—bypassing rigid gesture classification. For instance, a swift downward flick in the air over a noun phrase triggers deletion, while a looping hover followed by descent into writing initiates paraphrase; the LLM interprets these not as isolated commands but as contextually grounded actions, adjusting grammatical structure and agreement accordingly. A novel 'contextual insertion field' mechanism dynamically predicts optimal placement and inflection for handwritten replacements by analyzing local syntactic dependencies and common MT error profiles (e.g., article omissions, tense mismatches). Real-time feedback is provided via adaptive UI elements: deleted text fades with physics-based animation, and predictive inline suggestions appear only when confidence exceeds a threshold derived from motion fluency and lexical plausibility. To support accessibility and diverse workflows, FluidEdit operates in multiple engagement levels—from full 3D gesture for power users to minimal-touch handwriting for constrained environments. The system is designed to minimize cognitive and motor switching costs, making it ideal for high-throughput translation tasks in journalism, crisis response, and multilingual diplomacy. By reframing gesture not as a command set but as a modality of linguistic expression interpreted alongside text, FluidEdit establishes a new paradigm in AI-mediated human language interaction.\",\n  \"Title\": \"FluidEdit: Unified Motion and Language Modeling for Context-Aware Post-Editing of Machine Translation\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The implementation will follow five phases. Phase 1 involves building a multimodal capture rig combining a Wacom tablet with integrated proximity sensing, an Intel RealSense D455 depth camera for hand tracking, and synchronized logging of keystrokes, timing, and eye gaze (via Tobii Pro). Professional translators (n=20) will perform post-editing tasks across four language pairs (English-German, English-Japanese, English-Arabic, English-Spanish) using both standard tools and the prototype under guided scenarios (e.g., correcting named entities, restructuring passive voice). All motion, ink, and behavioral data will be recorded. Phase 2 focuses on dataset construction: motion sequences will be labeled with intention tags (delete, move, replace, etc.) via consensus coding, and paired with linguistic annotations (POS, dependency parse, MT error type). Phase 3 develops the joint embedding model: a cross-modal transformer will be trained to map motion and text into a shared intention space, using contrastive learning to align similar intents across modalities. Gesture classification emerges implicitly rather than being hard-coded. Phase 4 integrates the contextual insertion field—a graph-based module that models syntactic compatibility between handwritten insertions and surrounding clauses, informed by MT error priors extracted from benchmark datasets (e.g., WMT MQM). Phase 5 conducts a within-subjects user study comparing FluidEdit against GIF, keyboard/mouse, and pen-only baselines. Metrics include task time, edit accuracy (via TER and BERTScore), perceived workload (NASA-TLX), and qualitative interviews. Ideal outcomes: (1) 30% faster editing than baseline, (2) >90% gesture intent recognition accuracy without explicit segmentation, (3) significant reduction in corrective keystrokes due to intelligent insertion, and (4) strong user preference for fluid modality transitions.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 10\n}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[94mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "1afad6a9969e40669e5067b536d997a9", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:39:00", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "THOUGHT:  \nBoth Idea 0 (GIT) and Idea 1 (IED) propose highly innovative integrations of gesture-enhanced handwriting with language models for post-editing machine-translated text, leveraging multimodal inputs and LLMs in ways that go beyond current literature. However, when assessing novelty against the provided related papers, we must determine whether either idea significantly overlaps with existing work.\n\nPaper 1 (ImagiT), Paper 3, and Paper 5 all focus on multimodal machine translation (MMT) that incorporates visual imagination or synthetic images during translation—these are concerned with *how images or imagined visuals can improve translation generation*, not with *editing* translated text via user input modalities. Paper 2 (DE-Net) discusses dynamic text-guided image editing using adversarial networks, which is in the domain of image manipulation, not text editing. Paper 4 (DUnE) is the most relevant as it addresses model editing and defines a broad benchmark for natural language-guided edits to LMs, but it operates at the *model parameter level*—i.e., modifying internal knowledge representations—and does not involve user interface, gestures, handwriting, or real-time interaction.\n\nThus, none of the five papers address **real-time, multimodal, gesture-and-ink-based interfaces** for post-editing MT output with contextual insertion mechanics. Both proposed ideas fill this gap.\n\nHowever, between the two:\n\n- **Idea 0 (GIT)** focuses on *intent-driven post-editing* by fusing handwriting and gestures into executable editing commands using an LLM—a significant advance in multimodal HCI for NLP.\n- **Idea 1 (IED)** takes a deeper cognitive leap by modeling not just intent, but *imagined edits* derived from motor behavior (e.g., pressure, hesitation, doodles) as signals of semantic direction. It introduces the concept of \"edit imagination\" and uses embodied cues to infer abstract editorial goals like “make more formal” — going beyond action prediction to *intention modeling based on subtle behavioral biometrics*.\n\nThis shift from interpreting *what* to edit to inferring *why* and *in what direction* to edit based on motoric expressivity represents a **more radical conceptual departure** from existing paradigms. While GIT builds a powerful multimodal interface, IED reframes the entire interaction loop as a decoding of internal cognitive states through motor embodiment—an idea not explored in the cited papers or, to my knowledge, in current AI-HCI literature.\n\nTherefore, despite both being high-novelty proposals, **Idea 1 (IED)** demonstrates greater conceptual originality and theoretical risk, offering a new paradigm (\"imagined edit decoding\") rather than an improved interface. It also introduces a novel dataset (IMAGINE-MT) grounded in behavioral intentionality, further enhancing its contribution potential.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[91mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "b925c860421d4cd5918a1380126f229c", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:39:21", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "THOUGHT: \nBoth Idea 0 (Gesture-Ink Translator, GIT) and Idea 1 (Imagined Edit Decoding, IED) are highly novel, ambitious, and sit at the intersection of multimodal interaction, machine translation, and LLM integration. However, when evaluating against the provided related work for novelty and non-overlap, critical distinctions emerge.\n\nPaper 1 (ImagiT), Paper 3, and Paper 5 all focus on *multimodal machine translation*—specifically using visual imagination or synthetic images to improve translation quality. These are concerned with enhancing the *initial translation process*, not post-editing. Paper 2 (DE-Net) deals with image editing via text guidance and dynamic modules, which is thematically distant from handwriting or gesture-based text correction. Paper 4 (DUnE) addresses model editing—i.e., modifying internal knowledge of LMs—not user-driven post-editing of translated text outputs. Thus, none of the papers directly address *gesture-enhanced handwriting interfaces* for *post-editing MT output*, nor do they explore *contextual insertion mechanics* driven by multimodal inputs.\n\nBetween Idea 0 and Idea 1, both propose multimodal fusion of ink and gesture with LLMs, but **Idea 1 (IED)** takes a significantly more novel conceptual leap: it moves beyond interpreting gestures and handwriting as direct edit commands (as GIT does) and instead models them as *expressions of imagined intent*—a cognitive, embodied signal of editorial direction. This \"edit imagination\" framework—inferring semantic intent (e.g., “make more formal”) from motoric behavior (pressure, hesitation, gesture smoothness)—has no precedent in the literature cited or in mainstream HCI/NLP research. While GIT is innovative in its fusion mechanics, it remains within the established paradigm of *intent recognition as action prediction*. In contrast, IED redefines the problem space: from *what edit to apply* to *why the user wants to edit*, grounding LLM suggestions in behavioral proxies of cognition.\n\nFurthermore, IED's use of motor intentionality embeddings trained on force, velocity, eye-tracking, and gesture semantics—combined with generative modeling of *semantic directions* of change—represents a deeper theoretical contribution to human-AI collaboration. It introduces a new data modality (motor expressivity as semantic signal) and a new task (intent decoding from embodied behavior), which is not explored in any of the related papers.\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates greater conceptual novelty and a clearer departure from existing paradigms in MT, multimodal interfaces, and model editing.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[91mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "1f56c61310ea4b2fa78040552609d664", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:39:42", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "THOUGHT:  \nBoth Idea 0 (\"Gesture-Ink Fusion\") and Idea 1 (\"FluidEdit\") propose highly innovative approaches to combining gesture, handwriting, and language modeling for post-editing machine-translated text. However, when evaluating novelty against the provided related work, a critical distinction emerges.\n\nPaper 5 discusses LLM-based post-editing of MT using external error annotations (e.g., MQM), which is conceptually adjacent to contextual correction but relies on explicit textual feedback rather than multimodal input. Paper 2 (FELIX) introduces tagging and insertion for text editing, focusing on efficient NLP pipelines—not user interaction. Papers 3 and 4 (DUnE, MELO) deal with *model editing*—i.e., modifying internal model parameters or knowledge representations—not interactive user-driven text correction. Paper 1 (FLAME) involves text-to-motion generation, which is inverse in directionality (text → motion) and unrelated to editing via gestures.\n\nIdea 0 builds a two-stage system with explicit gesture classification and LLM-based interpretation. While novel, it aligns more closely with conventional multimodal architectures that separate gesture recognition from language understanding—a pattern seen in older HCI systems.\n\nIdea 1, however, proposes a **unified neural architecture** that co-processes stylus dynamics, in-air hand gestures, and linguistic context within a cross-modal transformer, bypassing rigid gesture segmentation through implicit intent decoding. This \"continuous spectrum of expressive intent\" and the concept of a 'contextual insertion field' informed by syntactic dependencies and MT error profiles represent a significant departure from existing paradigms. The integration of proximity sensing, 3D hand motion, and adaptive UI based on motion fluency pushes beyond current state-of-the-art in both HCI and AI-assisted translation. Crucially, no related paper addresses this level of sensor fusion combined with contextual language modeling for real-time, intention-aware text editing.\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates greater conceptual novelty by reframing gesture as a continuous, linguistically grounded modality interpreted jointly with text through an end-to-end learnable framework—something not explored in the cited literature.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[94mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "dae373768c804ad98ebb96811e14b2a8", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 17:39:59", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "THOUGHT: \nBoth Idea 0 (Gesture-Ink Fusion) and Idea 1 (FluidEdit) propose innovative approaches to combining gesture-enhanced handwriting with contextual language modeling for post-editing machine-translated text. However, when evaluating novelty against the provided related work, key distinctions emerge.\n\nPaper 2 (FELIX) and Paper 5 both address machine translation post-editing using language models, with FELIX focusing on efficient tagging and insertion, and Paper 5 exploring LLM guidance via error annotations—these are relevant but operate in the symbolic/textual domain without multimodal input. Papers 3 and 4 (DUnE and MELO) focus on model editing rather than user-driven text correction, making them less directly related. Paper 1 (FLAME) involves text-to-motion synthesis, which is conceptually inverse to the problem here—generating motion from language, not interpreting motion as linguistic intent.\n\nIdea 0 builds a two-stage system that classifies gestures into discrete primitives before fusing them with text via an LLM. While well-structured and feasible, this approach relies on explicit gesture classification—a paradigm seen in prior HCI systems (e.g., gesture recognizers feeding command inputs). This overlaps somewhat with conventional multimodal pipelines, reducing its novelty despite strong integration with LLMs.\n\nIn contrast, Idea 1 (FluidEdit) introduces a *unified neural architecture* that co-processes stylus dynamics, in-air hand gestures, and linguistic context within a cross-modal transformer, avoiding hard-coded gesture segmentation. It treats gesture as a continuous spectrum of intent and allows the LLM to decode \"intentional semantics\" implicitly through joint embedding. This moves beyond modular pipelines to a truly integrated, end-to-end interpretable motion-language model. The \"contextual insertion field\" further innovates 